    <remark>
      Notice that finding the domain and range can be tricky! Be sure to pay attention to the <m>x</m>- and <m>y</m>-values of the entire graph - not just the endpoints!
    </remark>

    <activity xml:id="finding-intervals-of-increase-and-decrease">
      <introduction>
        <p>
          In this activity, we will look at where the function is increasing and decreasing. Use the following graph to answer the questions below.
        </p>
          <image>
            <sageplot>
              f(x) = (-x^2-2*x+3)
              p=plot(f, (x, -4, 2),  ymin=-1, ymax=5, color='blue', thickness=3, detect_poles=True)
            </sageplot>
          </image>
      </introduction>
      <task>
        <p>
          Where do you think the graph is increasing?
        </p>
      </task>
      <task>
        <statement>
          <p>
            Which interval best represents where the function is increasing?
            <ol marker= "A." cols="2">
              <li> <m>(-\infty, -1]</m> </li>
              <li> <m>(-\infty, -1)</m> </li>
              <li> <m>(-1,\infty)</m> </li>
              <li> <m>[-1,\infty)</m> </li></ol></p>
        </statement>
        <answer>
          <p>
            Choice B: <m>(-\infty, -1)</m>
          </p>
        </answer>
      </task>
      <task>
        <p>
        Where do you think the graph is decreasing?
        </p>
      </task>
      <task>
        <statement>
          <p>
            Which interval best represents where the function is decreasing?
            <ol marker= "A." cols="2">
              <li> <m>(-\infty, -1]</m> </li>
              <li> <m>(-\infty, -1)</m> </li>
              <li> <m>(-1,\infty)</m> </li>
              <li> <m>[-1,\infty)</m> </li></ol></p>
        </statement>
        <answer>
          <p>
            Choice C: <m>(-1,\infty)</m>
          </p>
        </answer>
      </task>
      <task>
      <p>
        Based on what you see on the graph, do you think this graph has any maximums or minimums?
        </p>
      </task>
    </activity>

    <definition xml:id="def-intervals-of-increase-and-decrease-and-constant">
      <statement>
        <p>
          As you noticed in <xref ref="finding-intervals-of-increase-and-decrease"/>, functions can increase or decrease (or even remain constant!) for a period of time. The <term>interval of increase</term> is when the value of the function <m>f(x)</m> increases with an increase in the value of <m>x</m>. The <term>interval of decrease</term> is when the value of the function <m>f(x)</m> decreases with an increase in the value of <m>x</m>. The function is constant when the <m>y</m>-values remain constant as <m>x</m> increases (also known as the <term>constant interval</term>).
        </p>
        <p>
          The easiest way to identify these intervals is to read the graph from left to right and look at what is happening to the <m>y</m>-values.
        </p>
      </statement>
    </definition>

    <definition xml:id="def-max-and-min">
      <statement>
        <p>
          The <term>maximum value</term>, or <term>global maximum</term>, of a graph is the point where the <m>y</m>-coordinate has the largest value. The <term>minimum value</term>, or <term>global minimum</term> is the point on the graph where the <m>y</m>-coordinate has the smallest value.
        </p>
        <p>
          Graphs can also have <term>relative/local maximums</term> and <term>relative/local minimums</term>. A relative maximum point is a point where the function changes direction from increasing to decreasing (making that point a "hill" in the graph). Similarly, a relative minimum point is a point where the function changes direction from decreasing to increasing (making that point a "valley" in the graph).
        </p>
      </statement>
    </definition>

    <activity xml:id="distinguish-between-max-and-min">
      <introduction>
        <p>
          Use the following graph to answer the questions below.
        </p>
        <figure xml:id="graph-with-max-and-min-values">
            <image>
            <sageplot>
              p=plot(spline([(-4,4),(-2,7),(2,-4),(5,10)]),(x,-4,5),thickness=3)
              p+=point((-4,4),pointsize=50,color='blue',xmin=-7,xmax=8,ymin=-5,ymax=10)
              p+=point((5,10),pointsize=50,color='blue')
              p
            </sageplot>
          </image>
        </figure>
      </introduction>
      <task>
        <statement>
          <p>
            At what value of <m>x</m> is there a global maximum?
            <ol marker= "A." cols="2">
              <li> <m>x=-4</m> </li>
              <li> <m>x=-2</m> </li>
              <li> <m>x=2</m> </li>
              <li> <m>x=5</m> </li></ol></p>
        </statement>
        <answer>
          <p>
            Choice D: <m>x=5</m>
          </p>
        </answer>
      </task>
      <task>
        <statement>
          <p>
            What is the global maximum?
            <ol marker= "A." cols="2">
              <li> <m>10</m> </li>
              <li> <m>7</m> </li>
              <li> <m>4</m> </li>
              <li> <m>-4</m> </li></ol></p>
        </statement>
        <answer>
          <p>
            Choice A: <m>10</m>
          </p>
        </answer>
      </task>
      <task>
        <statement>
          <p>
            At what value of <m>x</m> is there a global minimum?
            <ol marker= "A." cols="2">
              <li> <m>x=-4</m> </li>
              <li> <m>x=-2</m> </li>
              <li> <m>x=2</m> </li>
              <li> <m>x=5</m> </li></ol></p>
        </statement>
        <answer>
          <p>
            Choice C: <m>x=2</m>
          </p>
        </answer>
      </task>
      <task>
        <statement>
          <p>
            What is the global minimum?
            <ol marker= "A." cols="2">
              <li> <m>10</m> </li>
              <li> <m>7</m> </li>
              <li> <m>4</m> </li>
              <li> <m>-4</m> </li></ol></p>
        </statement>
        <answer>
          <p>
            Choice D: <m>-4</m>
          </p>
        </answer>
      </task>
      <task>
        <statement>
          <p>
            At what value of <m>x</m> is there a local or relative maximum?
            <ol marker= "A." cols="2">
              <li> <m>x=-4</m> </li>
              <li> <m>x=-2</m> </li>
              <li> <m>x=2</m> </li>
              <li> <m>x=5</m> </li></ol></p>
        </statement>
        <answer>
          <p>
            Choice B: <m>x=-2</m>
          </p>
        </answer>
      </task>
      <task>
        <statement>
          <p>
            What is the local or relative maximum?
            <ol marker= "A." cols="2">
              <li> <m>10</m> </li>
              <li> <m>7</m> </li>
              <li> <m>4</m> </li>
              <li> <m>-4</m> </li></ol></p>
        </statement>
        <answer>
          <p>
            Choice B: <m>7</m>
          </p>
        </answer>
      </task>
      <task>
        <statement>
          <p>
            At what value of <m>x</m> is there a local or relative minimum?
            <ol marker= "A." cols="2">
              <li> <m>x=-4</m> </li>
              <li> <m>x=-2</m> </li>
              <li> <m>x=2</m> </li>
              <li> <m>x=5</m> </li></ol></p>
        </statement>
        <answer>
          <p>
            Choice C: <m>x=2</m>
          </p>
        </answer>
      </task>
      <task>
        <statement>
          <p>
            What is the local or relative minimum?
            <ol marker= "A." cols="2">
              <li> <m>10</m> </li>
              <li> <m>7</m> </li>
              <li> <m>4</m> </li>
              <li> <m>-4</m> </li></ol></p>
        </statement>
        <answer>
          <p>
            Choice D: <m>-4</m>
          </p>
        </answer>
      </task>
    </activity>

    <remark>
      Notice that in <xref ref="distinguish-between-max-and-min"/>, there are two ways we talk about max and min. We might want to know the location of where the max or min are (i.e., determining at which <m>x</m>-value the max or min occurs at) or we might want to know what the max or min are (i.e., the <m>y</m>-value). 
      <p> Also, note that in <xref ref="distinguish-between-max-and-min"/>, a local minimum is also a global minimum.
      </p>
    </remark>

